    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.37a.10"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">10</fw>
                
                <note>ans 5/8/73</note>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">PERU STATE COLLEGE
                        <lb/>
                    PERU, NEBRASKA 
                        <lb/>
                        
                    DIVISION OF HISTORY AND SOCIAL SCIENCE</hi> 
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>May 4, 1973</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Having attended two of your Peru State programs, a memory lingers of your comment that you have a soft spot in your heart for Peru State students. Would that spot have room for about 45 minutes spent with Peru students sometime during the afternoon of May 22?</p>
                
                <p>My husband George and I are the faculty guides for a 6-day tour of Nebraska. We start with 3 days of preliminary work on campus, followed by 6 days of travel by station wagon. A brochure is enclosed for your information. George has a Ph.D. in American history, I have a master's in English. The history majors on this tour will work with him, the English majors with me. He has taught at Peru State for 16 years, I for 6 years. During the tour he'll be concentrating on Nebraska history and geography, I on Nebraska writers, namely Mari Sandoz, Willa Cather, and you.</p> 
                
                <p>It would be the highlight of the trip to be able to include a visit with you at your Lincoln home. The group will number about 13 or 14 people who will be satisfied to sit on the floor (if necessary) to hear you read some of your poetry and converse for a short time.</p>
                
                <p>This is the first course of its kind ever given at Peru State. We weren't sure it would fill, therefore did not write to you until we knew definately<sic>definitely</sic>. This saves us the embarrassment of canceling a meeting you had prepared. We'll await your reply in the enclosed envelope, and will then phone you for final plans before we meet the students May 14.</p> 
                <closer>
                    <salute>Hopefully,</salute>
                
                    <signed>George &amp; Lillian Schottenhamel</signed>
                
                    <note>Our home phone: 872-3405</note>
                </closer>
                
                <fw>2</fw>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
